%U A394093 1,3,4,19,7,7,2,20,1,21,11,2,8,4,5,22,3,2
%N A394093 Greatest 0-based partial alternating sum of the prime indices of n.
%C A394093 After the first term, all terms are positive.
%C A394093 A prime index of n is a number m such that prime(m) divides n. The multiset of prime indices of n is row n of A112798.
%C A394093 The k-based partial alternating sums of a finite sequence q are given by pas(q,k)_j = (-1)^j * k + Sum_{i=1..j} (-1)^(i+j) * q_i. This is a signed version of the partial sums transformation, inverse to the "first sums" transformation. For example, the k-based partial alternating sums of q = (a,b,c,d,e) are:
%C A394093   pas(q,k)_0 =  k
%C A394093   pas(q,k)_1 = -k + a
%C A394093   pas(q,k)_2 =  k - a + b
%C A394093   pas(q,k)_3 = -k + a - b + c
%C A394093   pas(q,k)_4 =  k - a + b - c + d
%C A394093   pas(q,k)_5 = -k + a - b + c - d + e
%e A394093 The prime indices of 15 are (2,3), with 0-based partial alternating sums (0,2,1), so a(15) = 2.
%t A394093 prix[n_]:=If[n==1,{},Flatten[Cases[FactorInteger[n],{p_,k_}:>Table[PrimePi[p],{k}]]]];
%t A394093 pas[y_,k_]:=Table[(-1)^j*k+Sum[(-1)^(i+j)*y[[i]],{i,j}],{j,0,Length[y]}];
%t A394093 Table[Max@@pas[prix[n],0],{n,100}]
%Y A394093 For run-lengths instead of partial alternating sums we have A051903, for standard compositions A357137.
%Y A394093 For partial sums instead of partial alternating sums we have A056239.
%Y A394093 For last instead of maximum we have A344616, for standard compositions A344618.
%Y A394093 Row-maxima of A391981 and A392374, for standard compositions A391983, reverse A391984.
%Y A394093 For standard compositions we have A394091, row-maxima of A391983.
%Y A394093 For standard compositions and minimum we have A394092, trimmed A392713.
%Y A394093 A333766 gives maximum part of standard compositions, min A333768, first A065120, last A001511.
%Y A394093 A358136 lists partial sums of prime indices.
%Y A394093 Cf. A061395, A087117, A097805, A333219, A333767, A345197.
